parseInt.haxe_doc:
Native JavaScript `parseInt` function.
Its specification is different from `Std.parseInt`, so one might want to access the native one.

nativeThis.haxe_doc:
`nativeThis` is the JavaScript `this`, which is semantically different from the Haxe `this`. Use `nativeThis` only when working with external JavaScript code.
In Haxe, `this` is always bound to a class instance. In JavaScript, `this` in a function can be bound to an arbitrary variable when the function is called using `func.call(thisObj, ...)` or `func.apply(thisObj, [...])`.
Read more at https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/JavaScript/Reference/Operators/this

typeof.haxe_doc:
Call JavaScript `typeof` operator on the `o` value and return a string representing the JavaScript type of a value.
Read more at https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/JavaScript/Reference/Operators/typeof

global.haxe_doc:
An alias of the JS "global" object.
Concretely, it is set as the first defined value in the list of `window`, `global`, `self`, and `this` in the top-level of the compiled output.

class.haxe_doc: Platform-specific JavaScript Library. Provides some platform-specific functions for the JavaScript target.

addEventListener.haxe_doc: Register an event handler of a specific event type on the `EventTarget`. @throws DOMError
Register an event handler of a specific event type on the `EventTarget`. @throws DOMError

removeEventListener.haxe_doc: Removes an event listener from the `EventTarget`. @throws DOMError
Removes an event listener from the `EventTarget`. @throws DOMError

dispatchEvent.haxe_doc: Dispatch an event to this `EventTarget`. @throws DOMError

aborted.haxe_doc: A `Boolean` that indicates whether the request(s) the signal is communicating with is/are aborted (`true`) or not (`false`).

onabort.haxe_doc: Invoked when an `abort_(dom_abort_api)` event fires, i.e. when the DOM request(s) the signal is communicating with is/are aborted.

nodeType.haxe_doc:
Returns an unsigned short representing the type of the node. Possible values are: Name Value
ELEMENT_NODE 1
ATTRIBUTE_NODE (deprecated) 2
TEXT_NODE 3
CDATA_SECTION_NODE (deprecated) 4
ENTITY_REFERENCE_NODE (deprecated) 5
ENTITY_NODE (deprecated) 6
PROCESSING_INSTRUCTION_NODE 7
COMMENT_NODE 8
DOCUMENT_NODE 9
DOCUMENT_TYPE_NODE 10
DOCUMENT_FRAGMENT_NODE 11
NOTATION_NODE (deprecated) 12

nodeName.haxe_doc: Returns a `DOMString` containing the name of the `Node`. The structure of the name will differ with the node type. E.g. An `HTMLElement` will contain the name of the corresponding tag, like `'audio'` for an `HTMLAudioElement`, a `Text` node will have the `'#text'` string, or a `Document` node will have the `'#document'` string.

baseURI.haxe_doc: Returns a `DOMString` representing the base URL. The concept of base URL changes from one language to another; in HTML, it corresponds to the protocol, the domain name and the directory structure, that is all until the last `'/'`.

isConnected.haxe_doc: Returns a boolean indicating whether or not the Node is connected (directly or indirectly) to the context object, e.g. the `Document` object in the case of the normal DOM, or the `ShadowRoot` in the case of a shadow DOM.

ownerDocument.haxe_doc: Returns the `Document` that this node belongs to. If the node is itself a document, returns `null`.

parentNode.haxe_doc: Returns a `Node` that is the parent of this node. If there is no such node, like if this node is the top of the tree or if doesn't participate in a tree, this property returns `null`.

parentElement.haxe_doc: Returns an `Element` that is the parent of this node. If the node has no parent, or if that parent is not an `Element`, this property returns `null`.

childNodes.haxe_doc: Returns a live `NodeList` containing all the children of this node. `NodeList` being live means that if the children of the `Node` change, the `NodeList` object is automatically updated.

firstChild.haxe_doc: Returns a `Node` representing the first direct child node of the node, or `null` if the node has no child.

lastChild.haxe_doc: Returns a `Node` representing the last direct child node of the node, or `null` if the node has no child.

previousSibling.haxe_doc: Returns a `Node` representing the previous node in the tree, or `null` if there isn't such node.

nextSibling.haxe_doc: Returns a `Node` representing the next node in the tree, or `null` if there isn't such node.

nodeValue.haxe_doc: Returns / Sets the value of the current node

textContent.haxe_doc: Returns / Sets the textual content of an element and all its descendants.

getRootNode.haxe_doc: Returns the context object's root which optionally includes the shadow root if it is available.

hasChildNodes.haxe_doc: Returns a `Boolean` indicating if the element has any child nodes, or not.

insertBefore.haxe_doc: Inserts a `Node` before the reference node as a child of a specified parent node. @throws DOMError

replaceChild.haxe_doc: Replaces one child `Node` of the current one with the second one given in parameter. @throws DOMError

removeChild.haxe_doc: Removes a child node from the current element, which must be a child of the current node. @throws DOMError

normalize.haxe_doc: Clean up all the text nodes under this element (merge adjacent, remove empty).

cloneNode.haxe_doc: Clone a `Node`, and optionally, all of its contents. By default, it clones the content of the node. @throws DOMError

isSameNode.haxe_doc: Returns a `Boolean` value indicating whether or not the two nodes are the same (that is, they reference the same object).

isEqualNode.haxe_doc: Returns a `Boolean` which indicates whether or not two nodes are of the same type and all their defining data points match.

compareDocumentPosition.haxe_doc: Compares the position of the current node against another node in any other document.

contains.haxe_doc: Returns a `Boolean` value indicating whether a node is a descendant of a given node or not.

lookupPrefix.haxe_doc: Returns a `DOMString` containing the prefix for a given namespace URI, if present, and `null` if not. When multiple prefixes are possible, the result is implementation-dependent.

lookupNamespaceURI.haxe_doc: Accepts a prefix and returns the namespace URI associated with it on the given node if found (and `null` if not). Supplying `null` for the prefix will return the default namespace.

isDefaultNamespace.haxe_doc: Accepts a namespace URI as an argument and returns a `Boolean` with a value of `true` if the namespace is the default namespace on the given node or `false` if not.

namespaceURI.haxe_doc:
The namespace URI of the element, or `null` if it is no namespace.
Note: In Firefox 3.5 and earlier, HTML elements are in no namespace. In later versions, HTML elements are in the `http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml` namespace in both HTML and XML trees. `1.9.2`

prefix.haxe_doc: A `DOMString` representing the namespace prefix of the element, or `null` if no prefix is specified.

localName.haxe_doc: A `DOMString` representing the local part of the qualified name of the element.

tagName.haxe_doc: Returns a `String` with the name of the tag for the given element.

id.haxe_doc: Is a `DOMString` representing the id of the element.

className.haxe_doc: Is a `DOMString` representing the class of the element.

classList.haxe_doc: Returns a `DOMTokenList` containing the list of class attributes.

attributes.haxe_doc: Returns a `NamedNodeMap` object containing the assigned attributes of the corresponding HTML element.

scrollTop.haxe_doc: A `Number` representing number of pixels the top of the document is scrolled vertically.

scrollLeft.haxe_doc: Is a `Number` representing the left scroll offset of the element.

scrollWidth.haxe_doc: Returns a `Number` representing the scroll view width of the element.

scrollHeight.haxe_doc: Returns a `Number` representing the scroll view height of an element.

clientTop.haxe_doc: Returns a `Number` representing the width of the top border of the element.

clientLeft.haxe_doc: Returns a `Number` representing the width of the left border of the element.

clientWidth.haxe_doc: Returns a `Number` representing the inner width of the element.

clientHeight.haxe_doc: Returns a `Number` representing the inner height of the element.

scrollTopMax.haxe_doc: Returns a `Number` representing the maximum top scroll offset possible for the element.

scrollLeftMax.haxe_doc: Returns a `Number` representing the maximum left scroll offset possible for the element.

innerHTML.haxe_doc: Is a `DOMString` representing the markup of the element's content.

outerHTML.haxe_doc: Is a `DOMString` representing the markup of the element including its content. When used as a setter, replaces the element with nodes parsed from the given string.

shadowRoot.haxe_doc: Returns the open shadow root that is hosted by the element, or null if no open shadow root is present.

slot.haxe_doc: Returns the name of the shadow DOM slot the element is inserted in.

onwheel.haxe_doc: Returns the event handling code for the `wheel` event. This is now implemented on `GlobalEventHandlers.onwheel`.

ongotpointercapture.haxe_doc: Returns the event handler for the `gotpointercapture` event type.

onlostpointercapture.haxe_doc: Returns the event handler for the `lostpointercapture` event type.

getAttributeNames.haxe_doc: Returns an array of attribute names from the current element.

getAttribute.haxe_doc: Retrieves the value of the named attribute from the current node and returns it as an `Object`.

getAttributeNS.haxe_doc: Retrieves the value of the attribute with the specified name and namespace, from the current node and returns it as an `Object`.

toggleAttribute.haxe_doc: Toggles a boolean attribute, removing it if it is present and adding it if it is not present, on the specified element. @throws DOMError

setAttribute.haxe_doc: Sets the value of a named attribute of the current node. @throws DOMError

setAttributeNS.haxe_doc: Sets the value of the attribute with the specified name and namespace, from the current node. @throws DOMError

removeAttribute.haxe_doc: Removes the named attribute from the current node. @throws DOMError

removeAttributeNS.haxe_doc: Removes the attribute with the specified name and namespace, from the current node. @throws DOMError

hasAttribute.haxe_doc: Returns a `Boolean` indicating if the element has the specified attribute or not.

hasAttributeNS.haxe_doc: Returns a `Boolean` indicating if the element has the specified attribute, in the specified namespace, or not.

hasAttributes.haxe_doc: Returns a `Boolean` indicating if the element has one or more HTML attributes present.

closest.haxe_doc: Returns the `Element` which is the closest ancestor of the current element (or the current element itself) which matches the selectors given in parameter. @throws DOMError

matches.haxe_doc: Returns a `Boolean` indicating whether or not the element would be selected by the specified selector string. @throws DOMError

getElementsByTagName.haxe_doc: Returns a live `HTMLCollection` containing all descendant elements, of a particular tag name, from the current element.

getElementsByTagNameNS.haxe_doc: Returns a live `HTMLCollection` containing all descendant elements, of a particular tag name and namespace, from the current element. @throws DOMError

getElementsByClassName.haxe_doc: Returns a live `HTMLCollection` that contains all descendants of the current element that possess the list of classes given in the parameter.

insertAdjacentElement.haxe_doc: Inserts a given element node at a given position relative to the element it is invoked upon. @throws DOMError

insertAdjacentText.haxe_doc: Inserts a given text node at a given position relative to the element it is invoked upon. @throws DOMError

setPointerCapture.haxe_doc: Designates a specific element as the capture target of future pointer events. @throws DOMError

releasePointerCapture.haxe_doc: Releases (stops) pointer capture that was previously set for a specific `PointerEvent`. @throws DOMError

setCapture.haxe_doc: Sets up mouse event capture, redirecting all mouse events to this element.

getAttributeNode.haxe_doc: Retrieves the node representation of the named attribute from the current node and returns it as an `Attr`.

setAttributeNode.haxe_doc: Sets the node representation of the named attribute from the current node. @throws DOMError

removeAttributeNode.haxe_doc: Removes the node representation of the named attribute from the current node. @throws DOMError

getAttributeNodeNS.haxe_doc: Retrieves the node representation of the attribute with the specified name and namespace, from the current node and returns it as an `Attr`.

setAttributeNodeNS.haxe_doc: Sets the node representation of the attribute with the specified name and namespace, from the current node. @throws DOMError

getClientRects.haxe_doc: Returns a collection of rectangles that indicate the bounding rectangles for each line of text in a client.

getBoundingClientRect.haxe_doc: Returns the size of an element and its position relative to the viewport.

scrollIntoView.haxe_doc: Scrolls the page until the element gets into the view.
Scrolls the page until the element gets into the view.

insertAdjacentHTML.haxe_doc: Parses the text as HTML or XML and inserts the resulting nodes into the tree in the position given. @throws DOMError

querySelector.haxe_doc: Returns the first `Node` which matches the specified selector string relative to the element. @throws DOMError

querySelectorAll.haxe_doc: Returns a `NodeList` of nodes which match the specified selector string relative to the element. @throws DOMError

attachShadow.haxe_doc: Attatches a shadow DOM tree to the specified element and returns a reference to its `ShadowRoot`. @throws DOMError

requestFullscreen.haxe_doc: Asynchronously asks the browser to make the element full-screen. @throws DOMError

requestPointerLock.haxe_doc: Allows to asynchronously ask for the pointer to be locked on the given element.

animate.haxe_doc: A shortcut method to create and run an animation on an element. Returns the created Animation object instance. @throws DOMError
A shortcut method to create and run an animation on an element. Returns the created Animation object instance. @throws DOMError

getAnimations.haxe_doc: Returns an array of Animation objects currently active on the element.

click.haxe_doc: Sends a mouse click event to the element.

focus.haxe_doc: Makes the element the current keyboard focus. @throws DOMError

blur.haxe_doc: Removes keyboard focus from the currently focused element. @throws DOMError

target.haxe_doc: Is a `DOMString` that reflects the `target` HTML attribute, indicating where to display the linked resource.

download.haxe_doc: Is a `DOMString` indicating that the linked resource is intended to be downloaded rather than displayed in the browser. The value represent the proposed name of the file. If the name is not a valid filename of the underlying OS, browser will adapt it.

rel.haxe_doc: Is a `DOMString` that reflects the `rel` HTML attribute, specifying the relationship of the target object to the linked object.

referrerPolicy.haxe_doc: Is a `DOMString` that reflects the `referrerpolicy` HTML attribute indicating which referrer to use.

relList.haxe_doc: Returns a `DOMTokenList` that reflects the `rel` HTML attribute, as a list of tokens.

hreflang.haxe_doc: Is a `DOMString` that reflects the `hreflang` HTML attribute, indicating the language of the linked resource.

type.haxe_doc: Is a `DOMString` that reflects the `type` HTML attribute, indicating the MIME type of the linked resource.

text.haxe_doc: Is a `DOMString` being a synonym for the `Node.textContent` property.

coords.haxe_doc: Is a `DOMString` representing a comma-separated list of coordinates.

charset.haxe_doc: Is a `DOMString` representing the character encoding of the linked resource.

name.haxe_doc: Is a `DOMString` representing the anchor name.

rev.haxe_doc: Is a `DOMString` representing that the `rev` HTML attribute, specifying the relationship of the link object to the target object. Note: Currently the W3C HTML 5.2 spec states that `rev` is no longer obsolete, whereas the WHATWG living standard still has it labeled obsolete. Until this discrepancy is resolved, you should still assume it is obsolete.

shape.haxe_doc: Is a `DOMString` representing the shape of the active area.

id.haxe_doc: Gets and sets the `String` used to identify the animation.

effect.haxe_doc: Gets and sets the `AnimationEffectReadOnly` associated with this animation. This will usually be a `KeyframeEffect` object.

timeline.haxe_doc: Gets or sets the `AnimationTimeline` associated with this animation.

startTime.haxe_doc: Gets or sets the scheduled time when an animation's playback should begin.

currentTime.haxe_doc: The current time value of the animation in milliseconds, whether running or paused. If the animation lacks a `AnimationTimeline`, is inactive or hasn't been played yet, its value is `null`.

playbackRate.haxe_doc: Gets or sets the playback rate of the animation.

playState.haxe_doc: Returns an enumerated value describing the playback state of an animation.

pending.haxe_doc: Indicates whether the animation is currently waiting for an asynchronous operation such as initiating playback or pausing a running animation.

ready.haxe_doc: Returns the current ready Promise for this animation.

finished.haxe_doc: Returns the current finished Promise for this animation.

onfinish.haxe_doc: Gets and sets the event handler for the `finish` event.

oncancel.haxe_doc: Gets and sets the event handler for the `cancel` event.

cancel.haxe_doc: Clears all `KeyframeEffect` caused by this animation and aborts its playback.

finish.haxe_doc: Seeks either end of an animation, depending on whether the animation is playing or reversing. @throws DOMError

play.haxe_doc: Starts or resumes playing of an animation, or begins the animation again if it previously finished. @throws DOMError

pause.haxe_doc: Suspends playing of an animation. @throws DOMError

updatePlaybackRate.haxe_doc: Sets the speed of an animation after first synchronizing its playback position.

reverse.haxe_doc: Reverses playback direction, stopping at the start of the animation. If the animation is finished or unplayed, it will play from end to beginning. @throws DOMError

currentTime.haxe_doc: Returns the time value in milliseconds for this timeline or `null` if this timeline is inactive.

alt.haxe_doc: Is a `DOMString` that reflects the `alt` HTML attribute, containing alternative text for the element.

coords.haxe_doc: Is a `DOMString` that reflects the `coords` HTML attribute, containing coordinates to define the hot-spot region.

shape.haxe_doc: Is a `DOMString` that reflects the `shape` HTML attribute, indicating the shape of the hot-spot, limited to known values.

target.haxe_doc: Is a `DOMString` that reflects the `target` HTML attribute, indicating the browsing context in which to open the linked resource.

download.haxe_doc: Is a `DOMString` indicating that the linked resource is intended to be downloaded rather than displayed in the browser. The value represent the proposed name of the file. If the name is not a valid filename of the underlying OS, browser will adapt it.

rel.haxe_doc: Is a `DOMString` that reflects the `rel` HTML attribute, indicating relationships of the current document to the linked resource.

referrerPolicy.haxe_doc: Is a `DOMString` that reflects the `referrerpolicy` HTML attribute indicating which referrer to use when fetching the linked resource.

relList.haxe_doc: Returns a `DOMTokenList` that reflects the `rel` HTML attribute, indicating relationships of the current document to the linked resource, as a list of tokens.

noHref.haxe_doc: Is a `Boolean` flag indicating if the area is inactive (`true`) or active (`false`).

localName.haxe_doc: A `DOMString` representing the local part of the qualified name of the attribute.

name.haxe_doc: The attribute's name.

namespaceURI.haxe_doc: A `DOMString` representing the namespace URI of the attribute, or `null` if there is no namespace.

prefix.haxe_doc: A `DOMString` representing the namespace prefix of the attribute, or `null` if no prefix is specified.

specified.haxe_doc: This property always returns `true`. Originally, it returned `true `if the attribute was explicitly specified in the source code or by a script, and `false` if its value came from the default one defined in the document's DTD.

ownerElement.haxe_doc:
The element holding the attribute.
Note: DOM Level 4 removed this property. The assumption was that since you get an `Attr` object from an `Element`, you should already know the associated element.
As that doesn't hold true in cases like `Attr` objects being returned by `Document.evaluate`, the DOM Living Standard reintroduced the property.
Gecko outputs a deprecation note starting from Gecko 7.0 `7.0`. This note was removed again in Gecko 49.0 `49.0`.

error.haxe_doc: Returns a `MediaError` object for the most recent error, or `null` if there has not been an error.

src.haxe_doc: Is a `DOMString` that reflects the `src` HTML attribute, which contains the URL of a media resource to use.

currentSrc.haxe_doc: Returns a `DOMString` with the absolute URL of the chosen media resource.

crossOrigin.haxe_doc: Is a `DOMString` indicating the CORS setting for this media element.

networkState.haxe_doc: Returns a `unsigned short` (enumeration) indicating the current state of fetching the media over the network.

preload.haxe_doc: Is a `DOMString` that reflects the `preload` HTML attribute, indicating what data should be preloaded, if any. Possible values are: `none`, `metadata`, `auto`.

buffered.haxe_doc: Returns a `TimeRanges` object that indicates the ranges of the media source that the browser has buffered (if any) at the moment the `buffered` property is accessed.

readyState.haxe_doc: Returns a `unsigned short` (enumeration) indicating the readiness state of the media.

seeking.haxe_doc: Returns a `Boolean` that indicates whether the media is in the process of seeking to a new position.

currentTime.haxe_doc: Is a `double` indicating the current playback time in seconds. Setting this value seeks the media to the new time.

duration.haxe_doc: Returns a `double` indicating the length of the media in seconds, or 0 if no media data is available.

paused.haxe_doc: Returns a `Boolean` that indicates whether the media element is paused.

defaultPlaybackRate.haxe_doc: Is a `double` indicating the default playback rate for the media.

playbackRate.haxe_doc: Is a `double` that indicates the rate at which the media is being played back.

played.haxe_doc: Returns a `TimeRanges` object that contains the ranges of the media source that the browser has played, if any.

seekable.haxe_doc: Returns a `TimeRanges` object that contains the time ranges that the user is able to seek to, if any.

ended.haxe_doc: Returns a `Boolean` that indicates whether the media element has finished playing.

autoplay.haxe_doc: A `Boolean` that reflects the `autoplay` HTML attribute, indicating whether playback should automatically begin as soon as enough media is available to do so without interruption. Sites which automatically play audio (or videos with an audio track) can be an unpleasant experience for users, so it should be avoided when possible. If you must offer autoplay functionality, you should make it opt-in (requiring a user to specifically enable it). However, this can be useful when creating media elements whose source will be set at a later time, under user control.

loop.haxe_doc: Is a `Boolean` that reflects the `loop` HTML attribute, which indicates whether the media element should start over when it reaches the end.

controls.haxe_doc: Is a `Boolean` that reflects the `controls` HTML attribute, indicating whether user interface items for controlling the resource should be displayed.

volume.haxe_doc: Is a `double` indicating the audio volume, from 0.0 (silent) to 1.0 (loudest).

muted.haxe_doc: Is a `Boolean` that determines whether audio is muted. `true` if the audio is muted and `false` otherwise.

defaultMuted.haxe_doc: Is a `Boolean` that reflects the `muted` HTML attribute, which indicates whether the media element's audio output should be muted by default.

audioTracks.haxe_doc: A `AudioTrackList` that lists the `AudioTrack` objects contained in the element.

videoTracks.haxe_doc:
Returns the list of `VideoTrack` objects contained in the element.
Gecko supports only single track playback, and the parsing of tracks' metadata is only available for media with the Ogg container format.

textTracks.haxe_doc: Returns the list of `TextTrack` objects contained in the element.

srcObject.haxe_doc: Is a `MediaStream` representing the media to play or that has played in the current `HTMLMediaElement`, or `null` if not assigned.

mediaKeys.haxe_doc: Returns a `MediaKeys` object or `null`. MediaKeys is a set of keys that an associated HTMLMediaElement can use for decryption of media data during playback.

onencrypted.haxe_doc: Sets the `EventHandler` called when the media is encrypted.

onwaitingforkey.haxe_doc: Sets the `EventHandler` called when playback is blocked while waiting for an encryption key.

load.haxe_doc: Resets the media element and restarts the media resource. Any pending events are discarded. How much media data is fetched is still affected by the `preload` attribute. This method can be useful for releasing resources after any `src` attribute and `source` element descendants have been removed. Otherwise, it is usually unnecessary to use this method, unless required to rescan `source` element children after dynamic changes.

canPlayType.haxe_doc: Determines whether the specified media type can be played back.

fastSeek.haxe_doc: Directly seeks to the given time. @throws DOMError

play.haxe_doc: Begins playback of the media. @throws DOMError

addTextTrack.haxe_doc: Adds a text track (such as a track for subtitles) to a media element.

setMediaKeys.haxe_doc: Returns `Promise`. Sets the `MediaKeys` keys to use when decrypting media during playback.

kind.haxe_doc: Returns a `DOMString` set to `"audio"` if the track is an audio track and to `"video"`, if it is a video track. It doesn't change if the track is deassociated from its source.

id.haxe_doc: Returns a `DOMString` containing a unique identifier (GUID) for the track; it is generated by the browser.

label.haxe_doc: Returns a `DOMString` containing a user agent-assigned label that identifies the track source, as in `"internal microphone"`. The string may be left empty and is empty as long as no source has been connected. When the track is deassociated from its source, the label is not changed.

enabled.haxe_doc: A Boolean whose value of `true` if the track is enabled, that is allowed to render the media source stream; or `false` if it is disabled, that is not rendering the media source stream but silence and blackness. If the track has been disconnected, this value can be changed but has no more effect. Note: You can implement standard "mute" functionality by setting `enabled` to `false`. The `muted` property refers to a condition in which there's no media because of a technical issue.

muted.haxe_doc: Returns a Boolean value indicating whether the track is unable to provide media data due to a technical issue. Note: You can implement standard "mute" functionality by setting `enabled` to `false`, and unmute the media by setting it back to `true` again.

onmute.haxe_doc: An `EventHandler` containing the action to perform when an `mute` event is fired on the object, that is when the streaming is terminating.

onunmute.haxe_doc: An `EventHandler` containing the action to perform when an `unmute` event is fired on the object, that is when a `MediaStreamTrack` object is removed from it.

readyState.haxe_doc:
Returns an enumerated value giving the status of the track. This will be one of the following values:
`"live"` which indicates that an input is connected and does its best-effort in providing real-time data. In that case, the output of data can be switched on or off using the `MediaStreamTrack.enabled` attribute. `"ended"` which indicates that the input is not giving any more data and will never provide new data.

onended.haxe_doc: An `EventHandler` containing the action to perform when an `ended_(MediaStream)` event is fired on the object, that is when a `MediaStreamTrack` object is removed from it.

stop.haxe_doc: Stops playing the source associated to the track, both the source and the track are deassociated. The track state is set to `ended`.

getConstraints.haxe_doc: Returns a `MediaTrackConstraints` object containing the currently set constraints for the track; the returned value matches the constraints last set using `MediaStreamTrack.applyConstraints`.

getSettings.haxe_doc: Returns a `MediaTrackSettings` object containing the current values of each of the `MediaStreamTrack`'s constrainable properties.

applyConstraints.haxe_doc: Lets the application specify the ideal and/or ranges of acceptable values for any number of the available constrainable properties of the `MediaStreamTrack`. @throws DOMError

id.haxe_doc: A `DOMString` which uniquely identifies the track within the media. This ID can be used to locate a specific track within an audio track list by calling `AudioTrackList.getTrackById()`. The ID can also be used as the fragment part of the URL if the media supports seeking by media fragment per the Media Fragments URI specification.

kind.haxe_doc: A `DOMString` specifying the category into which the track falls. For example, the main audio track would have a `kind` of `"main"`.

label.haxe_doc: A `DOMString` providing a human-readable label for the track. For example, an audio commentary track for a movie might have a `label` of `"Commentary with director John Q. Public and actors John Doe and Jane Eod."` This string is empty if no label is provided.

language.haxe_doc: A `DOMString` specifying the audio track's primary language, or an empty string if unknown. The language is specified as a BCP 47 ({{RFC(5646)}}) language code, such as `"en-US"` or `"pt-BR"`.

enabled.haxe_doc: A Boolean value which controls whether or not the audio track's sound is enabled. Setting this value to `false` mutes the track's audio.

length.haxe_doc: The number of tracks in the list.

clear.haxe_doc: Is a `DOMString` indicating the flow of text around floating objects.

href.haxe_doc: Is a `DOMString` that reflects the `href` HTML attribute, containing a base URL for relative URLs in the document.

target.haxe_doc: Is a `DOMString` that reflects the `target` HTML attribute, containing a default target browsing context or frame for elements that do not have a target reference specified.

size.haxe_doc: The size, in bytes, of the data contained in the `Blob` object.

type.haxe_doc: A string indicating the MIME type of the data contained in the `Blob`. If the type is unknown, this string is empty.

slice.haxe_doc: Returns a new `Blob` object containing the data in the specified range of bytes of the source `Blob`. @throws DOMError

text.haxe_doc: Is a `DOMString` that represents the foreground color of text.

link.haxe_doc: Is a `DOMString` that represents the color of unvisited links.

vLink.haxe_doc: Is a `DOMString` that represents the color of visited links.

aLink.haxe_doc: Is a `DOMString` that represents the color of active hyperlinks.

bgColor.haxe_doc: Is a `DOMString` that represents the background color for the document.

background.haxe_doc: Is a `DOMString` that represents the description of the location of the background image resource. Note that this is not an URI, though some older version of some browsers do expect it.

autofocus.haxe_doc: Is a `Boolean` indicating whether or not the control should have input focus when the page loads, unless the user overrides it, for example by typing in a different control. Only one form-associated element in a document can have this attribute specified.

disabled.haxe_doc: Is a `Boolean` indicating whether or not the control is disabled, meaning that it does not accept any clicks.

form.haxe_doc:
Is a `HTMLFormElement` reflecting the form that this button is associated with. If the button is a descendant of a form element, then this attribute is the ID of that form element.
If the button is not a descendant of a form element, then the attribute can be the ID of any form element in the same document it is related to, or the `null` value if none matches.

formAction.haxe_doc: Is a `DOMString` reflecting the URI of a resource that processes information submitted by the button. If specified, this attribute overrides the `action` attribute of the `form` element that owns this element.

formEnctype.haxe_doc: Is a `DOMString` reflecting the type of content that is used to submit the form to the server. If specified, this attribute overrides the `enctype` attribute of the `form` element that owns this element.

formMethod.haxe_doc: Is a `DOMString` reflecting the HTTP method that the browser uses to submit the form. If specified, this attribute overrides the `method` attribute of the `form` element that owns this element.

formNoValidate.haxe_doc: Is a `Boolean` indicating that the form is not to be validated when it is submitted. If specified, this attribute overrides the `novalidate` attribute of the `form` element that owns this element.

formTarget.haxe_doc: Is a `DOMString` reflecting a name or keyword indicating where to display the response that is received after submitting the form. If specified, this attribute overrides the `target` attribute of the `form` element that owns this element.

name.haxe_doc: Is a `DOMString` representing the name of the object when submitted with a form. {{HTMLVersionInline(5)}} If specified, it must not be the empty string.

type.haxe_doc: Is a `DOMString` indicating the behavior of the button. This is an enumerated attribute with the following possible values: `"submit"`: The button submits the form. This is the default value if the attribute is not specified, {{HTMLVersionInline(5)}} or if it is dynamically changed to an empty or invalid value. `"reset"`: The button resets the form. `"button"`: The button does nothing. `"menu"`: The button displays a menu. (experimental)

value.haxe_doc: Is a `DOMString` representing the current form control value of the button.

willValidate.haxe_doc: Is a `Boolean` indicating whether the button is a candidate for constraint validation. It is `false` if any conditions bar it from constraint validation.

validity.haxe_doc: Is a `ValidityState` representing the validity states that this button is in.

validationMessage.haxe_doc: Is a `DOMString` representing the localized message that describes the validation constraints that the control does not satisfy (if any). This attribute is the empty string if the control is not a candidate for constraint validation (`willValidate` is `false`), or it satisfies its constraints.

labels.haxe_doc: Is a `NodeList` that represents a list of `label` elements that are labels for this button.

data.haxe_doc: Is a `DOMString` representing the textual data contained in this object.

length.haxe_doc: Returns an `unsigned long` representing the size of the string contained in `CharacterData.data`.

substringData.haxe_doc: Returns a `DOMString` containing the part of `CharacterData.data` of the specified length and starting at the specified offset. @throws DOMError

appendData.haxe_doc: Appends the given `DOMString` to the `CharacterData.data` string; when this method returns, `data` contains the concatenated `DOMString`. @throws DOMError

insertData.haxe_doc: Inserts the specified characters, at the specified offset, in the `CharacterData.data` string; when this method returns, `data` contains the modified `DOMString`. @throws DOMError

deleteData.haxe_doc: Removes the specified amount of characters, starting at the specified offset, from the `CharacterData.data` string; when this method returns, `data` contains the shortened `DOMString`. @throws DOMError

replaceData.haxe_doc: Replaces the specified amount of characters, starting at the specified offset, with the specified `DOMString`; when this method returns, `data` contains the modified `DOMString`. @throws DOMError

wholeText.haxe_doc: Returns a `DOMString` containing the text of all `Text` nodes logically adjacent to this `Node`, concatenated in document order.

filter.haxe_doc: Shorthand for the "filter" CSS property.

width.haxe_doc: Shorthand for the "width" CSS property.

type.haxe_doc: Returns a `DOMString` representing the style sheet language for this style sheet.

href.haxe_doc: Returns a `DOMString` representing the location of the stylesheet.

ownerNode.haxe_doc: Returns a `Node` associating this style sheet with the current document.

parentStyleSheet.haxe_doc: Returns a `StyleSheet` including this one, if any; returns `null` if there aren't any.

title.haxe_doc: Returns a `DOMString` representing the advisory title of the current style sheet.

media.haxe_doc: Returns a `MediaList` representing the intended destination medium for style information.

disabled.haxe_doc: Is a `Boolean` representing whether the current stylesheet has been applied or not.

ownerRule.haxe_doc: If this style sheet is imported into the document using an `@import` rule, the `ownerRule` property will return that `CSSImportRule`, otherwise it returns `null`.

cssRules.haxe_doc:
Returns a live `CSSRuleList`, listing the `CSSRule` objects in the style sheet.
This is normally used to access individual rules like this:
` styleSheet.cssRules[i] // where i = 0..cssRules.length-1`
To add or remove items in `cssRules`, use the `CSSStyleSheet`'s `deleteRule()` and `insertRule()` methods, described below.

insertRule.haxe_doc: Inserts a new rule at the specified position in the style sheet, given the textual representation of the rule. @throws DOMError

deleteRule.haxe_doc: Deletes a rule at the specified position from the style sheet. @throws DOMError

match.haxe_doc: Checks if a given `Request` is a key in any of the `Cache` objects that the `CacheStorage` object tracks, and returns a `Promise` that resolves to that match.
Checks if a given `Request` is a key in any of the `Cache` objects that the `CacheStorage` object tracks, and returns a `Promise` that resolves to that match.

has.haxe_doc: Returns a `Promise` that resolves to `true` if a `Cache` object matching the `cacheName` exists.

open.haxe_doc: Returns a `Promise` that resolves to the `Cache` object matching the `cacheName` (a new cache is created if it doesn't already exist.)

delete.haxe_doc: Finds the `Cache` object matching the `cacheName`, and if found, deletes the `Cache` object and returns a `Promise` that resolves to `true`. If no `Cache` object is found, it returns `false`.

keys.haxe_doc: Returns a `Promise` that will resolve with an array containing strings corresponding to all of the named `Cache` objects tracked by the `CacheStorage`. Use this method to iterate over a list of all the `Cache` objects.

id.haxe_doc: A `DOMString` containing 36 characters denoting a universally unique identifier (UUID) for the object.

active.haxe_doc: A Boolean value that returns `true` if the `MediaStream` is active, or `false` otherwise.

onaddtrack.haxe_doc: An `EventHandler` containing the action to perform when an `addtrack` event is fired when a new `MediaStreamTrack` object is added.

onremovetrack.haxe_doc: An `EventHandler` containing the action to perform when a `removetrack` event is fired when a `MediaStreamTrack` object is removed from it.

getAudioTracks.haxe_doc: Returns a list of the `MediaStreamTrack` objects stored in the MediaStream` object that have their kind` attribute set to "audio"`. The order is not defined, and may not only vary from one browser to another, but also from one call to another.

getVideoTracks.haxe_doc: Returns a list of the `MediaStreamTrack` objects stored in the `MediaStream` object that have their `kind` attribute set to `"video"`. The order is not defined, and may not only vary from one browser to another, but also from one call to another.

getTracks.haxe_doc: Returns a list of all `MediaStreamTrack` objects stored in the `MediaStream` object, regardless of the value of the `kind` attribute. The order is not defined, and may not only vary from one browser to another, but also from one call to another.

getTrackById.haxe_doc: Returns the track whose ID corresponds to the one given in parameters, trackid`. If no parameter is given, or if no track with that ID does exist, it returns null`. If several tracks have the same ID, it returns the first one.

addTrack.haxe_doc: Stores a copy of the `MediaStreamTrack` given as argument. If the track has already been added to the `MediaStream` object, nothing happens.

removeTrack.haxe_doc: Removes the `MediaStreamTrack` given as argument. If the track is not part of the MediaStream` object, nothing happens.

clone.haxe_doc: Returns a clone of the `MediaStream` object. The clone will, however, have a unique value for `MediaStream.id`.

width.haxe_doc: Is a positive `integer` reflecting the `width` HTML attribute of the `canvas` element interpreted in CSS pixels. When the attribute is not specified, or if it is set to an invalid value, like a negative, the default value of `300` is used.

height.haxe_doc: Is a positive `integer` reflecting the `height` HTML attribute of the `canvas` element interpreted in CSS pixels. When the attribute is not specified, or if it is set to an invalid value, like a negative, the default value of `150` is used.

getContext.haxe_doc: Returns a drawing context on the canvas, or null if the context ID is not supported. A drawing context lets you draw on the canvas. Calling getContext with `"2d"` returns a `CanvasRenderingContext2D` object, whereas calling it with `"webgl"` (or `"experimental-webgl"`) returns a `WebGLRenderingContext` object. This context is only available on browsers that implement WebGL. @throws DOMError

toDataURL.haxe_doc: Returns a data-URL containing a representation of the image in the format specified by the `type` parameter (defaults to `png`). The returned image is in a resolution of 96dpi. @throws DOMError

toBlob.haxe_doc: Creates a `Blob` object representing the image contained in the canvas; this file may be cached on the disk or stored in memory at the discretion of the user agent. @throws DOMError

captureStream.haxe_doc: Returns a `CanvasCaptureMediaStream` that is a real-time video capture of the surface of the canvas. @throws DOMError

addColorStop.haxe_doc: Adds a new stop, defined by an `offset` and a `color`, to the gradient. If the offset is not between `0` and `1` an `INDEX_SIZE_ERR` is raised, if the color can't be parsed as a CSS `color`, a `SYNTAX_ERR` is raised. @throws DOMError

setTransform.haxe_doc: Applies an `SVGMatrix` representing a linear transform to the pattern.

offsetNode.haxe_doc: Returns a `Node` containing the found node at the caret's position.

offset.haxe_doc: Returns a `long` representing the character offset in the caret position node.

read.haxe_doc: Requests arbitrary data (such as images) from the clipboard, returning a `Promise`. When the data has been retrieved, the promise is resolved with a `DataTransfer` object that provides the data. @throws DOMError

readText.haxe_doc: Requests text from the system clipboard; returns a `Promise` which is resolved with a `DOMString` containing the clipboard's text once it's available. @throws DOMError

write.haxe_doc: Writes arbitrary data to the system clipboard. This asynchronous operation signals that it's finished by resolving the returned `Promise`. @throws DOMError

writeText.haxe_doc: Writes text to the system clipboard, returning a `Promise` which is resolved once the text is fully copied into the clipboard. @throws DOMError

iterations.haxe_doc: The number of times the animation should repeat. Defaults to `1`, and can also take a value of `Infinity` to make it repeat for as long as the element exists.

iterationStart.haxe_doc: Describes at what point in the iteration the animation should start. 0.5 would indicate starting halfway through the first iteration for example, and with this value set, an animation with 2 iterations would end halfway through a third iteration. Defaults to 0.0.

fill.haxe_doc: Dictates whether the animation's effects should be reflected by the element(s) prior to playing (`"backwards"`), retained after the animation has completed playing (`"forwards"`), or `both`. Defaults to `"none"`.

endDelay.haxe_doc: The number of milliseconds to delay after the end of an animation. This is primarily of use when sequencing animations based on the end time of another animation. Defaults to 0.

easing.haxe_doc: The rate of the animation's change over time. Accepts the pre-defined values `"linear"`, `"ease"`, `"ease-in"`, `"ease-out"`, and `"ease-in-out"`, or a custom `"cubic-bezier"` value like `"cubic-bezier(0.42, 0, 0.58, 1)"`. Defaults to `"linear"`.

duration.haxe_doc: The number of milliseconds each iteration of the animation takes to complete. Defaults to 0. Although this is technically optional, keep in mind that your animation will not run if this value is 0.

direction.haxe_doc: Whether the animation runs forwards (`normal`), backwards (`reverse`), switches direction after each iteration (`alternate`), or runs backwards and switches direction after each iteration (`alternate-reverse`). Defaults to `"normal"`.

delay.haxe_doc: The number of milliseconds to delay the start of the animation. Defaults to 0.

assert.haxe_doc: Log a message and stack trace to console if the first argument is `false`.

count.haxe_doc: Log the number of times this line has been called with the given label.

countReset.haxe_doc: Resets the value of the counter with the given label.

debug.haxe_doc: Outputs a message to the console with the log level `"debug"`. Note: Starting with Chromium 58 this method only appears in Chromium browser consoles when level "Verbose" is selected.

error.haxe_doc: Outputs an error message. You may use string substitution and additional arguments with this method.

info.haxe_doc: Informative logging of information. You may use string substitution and additional arguments with this method.

log.haxe_doc: For general output of logging information. You may use string substitution and additional arguments with this method.

table.haxe_doc: Displays tabular data as a table.

warn.haxe_doc: Outputs a warning message. You may use string substitution and additional arguments with this method.

dir.haxe_doc: Displays an interactive listing of the properties of a specified JavaScript object. This listing lets you use disclosure triangles to examine the contents of child objects.

dirxml.haxe_doc: Displays an XML/HTML Element representation of the specified object if possible or the JavaScript Object view if it is not possible.

group.haxe_doc: Creates a new inline group, indenting all following output by another level. To move back out a level, call `groupEnd()`.

groupCollapsed.haxe_doc: Creates a new inline group, indenting all following output by another level. However, unlike `group()` this starts with the inline group collapsed requiring the use of a disclosure button to expand it. To move back out a level, call `groupEnd()`.

time.haxe_doc: Starts a timer with a name specified as an input parameter. Up to 10,000 simultaneous timers can run on a given page.

timeLog.haxe_doc: Logs the value of the specified timer to the console.

timeEnd.haxe_doc: Stops the specified timer and logs the elapsed time in seconds since it started.

timeStamp.haxe_doc: Adds a marker to the browser's Timeline or Waterfall tool.

profile.haxe_doc: Starts the browser's built-in profiler (for example, the Firefox performance tool). You can specify an optional name for the profile.

profileEnd.haxe_doc: Stops the profiler. You can see the resulting profile in the browser's performance tool (for example, the Firefox performance tool).

speed.haxe_doc: Returns a `double` representing the velocity of the device in meters per second. This value can be `null`.

longitude.haxe_doc: Returns a `double` representing the position's longitude in decimal degrees.

latitude.haxe_doc: Returns a `double` representing the position's latitude in decimal degrees.

heading.haxe_doc: Returns a `double` representing the direction in which the device is traveling. This value, specified in degrees, indicates how far off from heading true north the device is. `0` degrees represents true north, and the direction is determined clockwise (which means that east is `90` degrees and west is `270` degrees). If `speed` is `0`, `heading` is `NaN`. If the device is unable to provide `heading` information, this value is `null`.

altitudeAccuracy.haxe_doc: Returns a `double` representing the accuracy of the `altitude` expressed in meters. This value can be `null`.

altitude.haxe_doc: Returns a `double` representing the position's altitude in meters, relative to sea level. This value can be `null` if the implementation cannot provide the data.

accuracy.haxe_doc: Returns a `double` representing the accuracy of the `latitude` and `longitude` properties, expressed in meters.

subtle.haxe_doc: Returns a `SubtleCrypto` object providing access to common cryptographic primitives, like hashing, signing, encryption or decryption.

getRandomValues.haxe_doc: Fills the passed `TypedArray` with cryptographically sound random values. @throws DOMError

type.haxe_doc: Returns an enumerated value representing the type of the key, a secret key (for symmetric algorithm), a public or a private key (for an asymmetric algorithm)

extractable.haxe_doc: Returns a `Boolean` indicating if the raw information may be exported to the application or not.

algorithm.haxe_doc: Returns an opaque object representing a particular cipher the key has to be used with.

usages.haxe_doc: Returns an array of enumerated values indicating what the key can be used for.

compact.haxe_doc: Is a `Boolean` indicating that spacing between list items should be reduced.

name.haxe_doc: Returns a `DOMString` that contains one of the strings associated with an error name.

message.haxe_doc: Returns a `DOMString` representing a message or description associated with the given error name.

code.haxe_doc: Returns a `short` that contains one of the `Error codes`, or `0` if none match. This field is used for historical reasons. New DOM exceptions don't use this anymore: they put this info in the `DOMException.name` attribute.

hasFeature.haxe_doc: Returns a `Boolean` indicating if a given feature is supported or not. This function is unreliable and kept for compatibility purpose alone: except for SVG-related queries, it always returns `true`. Old browsers are very inconsistent in their behavior.

createHTMLDocument.haxe_doc: Creates and returns an HTML `Document`. @throws DOMError

toJSON.haxe_doc: Returns a JSON representation of the `DOMPointReadOnly` object.

z.haxe_doc: An unrestricted floating-point value which gives the point's z-coordinate, which is (assuming no transformations that alter the situation) the depth coordinate; positive values are closer to the user and negative values retreat back into the screen. The default value is 0.

y.haxe_doc: An unrestricted floating-point number providing the point's y-coordinate. This is the vertical coordinate, and barring any transforms applied to the coordinate system, positive values are downward and negative values upward toward the top of the screen. The default is 0.

x.haxe_doc: An unrestricted floating-point value indicating the x-coordinate of the point in space. This is generally the horizontal coordinate, with positive values being to the right and negative values to the left. The default value is 0.

w.haxe_doc: The point's w perspective value given as an unrestricted floating-point number. The default is 1.

p1.haxe_doc: are `DOMPoint` objects for each of the `DOMQuad` object's four corners.

getBounds.haxe_doc: Returns a `DOMRect` object with the coordinates and dimensions of the `DOMQuad` object.

toJSON.haxe_doc: Returns a JSON representation of the `DOMQuad` object.

x.haxe_doc: The x coordinate of the `DOMRect`'s origin.

y.haxe_doc: The y coordinate of the `DOMRect`'s origin.

width.haxe_doc: The width of the `DOMRect`.

top.haxe_doc: Returns the top coordinate value of the `DOMRect` (usually the same as `y`.)

right.haxe_doc: Returns the right coordinate value of the `DOMRect` (usually the same as `x + width`).

bottom.haxe_doc: Returns the bottom coordinate value of the `DOMRect` (usually the same as y + height).

left.haxe_doc: Returns the left coordinate value of the `DOMRect` (usually the same as `x`).

length.haxe_doc: Returns the length of the list,

contains.haxe_doc: Returns `Boolean` indicating if the given string is in the list

length.haxe_doc: Is an `integer` representing the number of objects stored in the object.

value.haxe_doc: The value of the list as a `DOMString`.

item.haxe_doc: Returns an item in the list by its index (returns undefined if the number is greater than or equal to the length of the list).

contains.haxe_doc: Returns `true` if the list contains the given token, otherwise `false`.

add.haxe_doc: Adds the given token to the list. @throws DOMError

remove.haxe_doc: Removes the specified token from the list. @throws DOMError

replace.haxe_doc: Replaces an existing token with a new token. @throws DOMError

toggle.haxe_doc: Removes a given token from the list and returns false. If token doesn't exist it's added and the function returns `true`. @throws DOMError

supports.haxe_doc: Returns `true` if a given token is in the associated attribute's supported tokens. @throws DOMError

options.haxe_doc: Is a `HTMLCollection` representing a collection of the contained option elements.

dropEffect.haxe_doc: Gets the type of drag-and-drop operation currently selected or sets the operation to a new type. The value must be `none`, `copy`, `link` or `move`.

effectAllowed.haxe_doc: Provides all of the types of operations that are possible. Must be one of `none`, `copy`, `copyLink`, `copyMove`, `link`, `linkMove`, `move`, `all` or `uninitialized`.

items.haxe_doc: Gives a `DataTransferItemList` object which is a list of all of the drag data.

types.haxe_doc: An array of `DOMString` giving the formats that were set in the `dragstart` event.

files.haxe_doc: Contains a list of all the local files available on the data transfer. If the drag operation doesn't involve dragging files, this property is an empty list.

setDragImage.haxe_doc: Set the image to be used for dragging if a custom one is desired.

getData.haxe_doc: Retrieves the data for a given type, or an empty string if data for that type does not exist or the data transfer contains no data. @throws DOMError

setData.haxe_doc: Set the data for a given type. If data for the type does not exist, it is added at the end, such that the last item in the types list will be the new format. If data for the type already exists, the existing data is replaced in the same position. @throws DOMError

clearData.haxe_doc: Remove the data associated with a given type. The type argument is optional. If the type is empty or not specified, the data associated with all types is removed. If data for the specified type does not exist, or the data transfer contains no data, this method will have no effect. @throws DOMError

addElement.haxe_doc: Sets the drag source to the given element. @throws DOMError

kind.haxe_doc: The kind of drag data item, `string` or `file`.

type.haxe_doc: The drag data item's type, typically a MIME type.

getAsString.haxe_doc: Invokes the specified callback with the drag data item string as its argument. @throws DOMError

getAsFile.haxe_doc: Returns the `File` object associated with the drag data item (or null if the drag item is not a file). @throws DOMError

length.haxe_doc: An `unsigned long` that is the number of drag items in the list.

add.haxe_doc: Adds an item (either a `File` object or a `DOMString`) to the drag item list and returns a `DataTransferItem` object for the new item. @throws DOMError
Adds an item (either a `File` object or a `DOMString`) to the drag item list and returns a `DataTransferItem` object for the new item. @throws DOMError

remove.haxe_doc: Removes the drag item from the list at the given index. @throws DOMError

clear.haxe_doc: Removes all of the drag items from the list. @throws DOMError

open.haxe_doc: Is a `boolean` reflecting the `open` HTML attribute, indicating whether or not the element’s contents (not counting the `summary`) is to be shown to the user.
A `Boolean` reflecting the open HTML attribute, indicating whether the dialog is available for interaction.

returnValue.haxe_doc: A `DOMString` that sets or returns the return value for the dialog.

close.haxe_doc: Closes the dialog. An optional `DOMString` may be passed as an argument, updating the `returnValue` of the the dialog.

show.haxe_doc: Displays the dialog modelessly, i.e. still allowing interaction with content outside of the dialog.

showModal.haxe_doc: Displays the dialog as a modal, over the top of any other dialogs that might be present. Interaction outside the dialog is blocked.

align.haxe_doc: Is a `DOMString` representing an enumerated property indicating alignment of the element's contents with respect to the surrounding context. The possible values are `"left"`, `"right"`, `"justify"`, and `"center"`.

implementation.haxe_doc: Returns the DOM implementation associated with the current document.

URL.haxe_doc: Returns the document location as a string.

documentURI.haxe_doc: Returns the document location as a string.

compatMode.haxe_doc: Indicates whether the document is rendered in quirks or strict mode.

characterSet.haxe_doc: Returns the character set being used by the document.

charset.haxe_doc: Alias of `Document.characterSet`. Use this property instead.

inputEncoding.haxe_doc: Alias of `Document.characterSet`. Use this property instead.

contentType.haxe_doc: Returns the Content-Type from the MIME Header of the current document.

doctype.haxe_doc: Returns the Document Type Definition (DTD) of the current document.

documentElement.haxe_doc: Returns the `Element` that is a direct child of the document. For HTML documents, this is normally the `HTMLElement` element.

location.haxe_doc: Returns the URI of the current document.

referrer.haxe_doc: Returns the URI of the page that linked to this page.

lastModified.haxe_doc: Returns the date on which the document was last modified.

readyState.haxe_doc: Returns loading status of the document.

title.haxe_doc: Sets or gets the title of the current document.

body.haxe_doc: Returns the `body` or `frameset` node of the current document.

head.haxe_doc: Returns the `head` element of the current document.

images.haxe_doc: Returns a list of the images in the current document.

embeds.haxe_doc: Returns a list of the embedded `embed` elements within the current document.

plugins.haxe_doc: Returns a list of the available plugins.

links.haxe_doc: Returns a list of all the hyperlinks in the document.

forms.haxe_doc: Returns a list of the `form` elements within the current document.

scripts.haxe_doc: Returns all the `script` elements on the document.

defaultView.haxe_doc: Returns a reference to the window object.

onreadystatechange.haxe_doc: Represents the event handling code for the `readystatechange` event.

onbeforescriptexecute.haxe_doc: Represents the event handling code for the `beforescriptexecute` event.

onafterscriptexecute.haxe_doc: Represents the event handling code for the `afterscriptexecute` event.

onselectionchange.haxe_doc: Is an `EventHandler` representing the code to be called when the `selectionchange` event is raised.

anchors.haxe_doc: Returns a list of all of the anchors in the document.

applets.haxe_doc: Returns an ordered list of the applets within a document.

onfullscreenchange.haxe_doc: Is an `EventHandler` representing the code to be called when the `fullscreenchange` event is raised.

onfullscreenerror.haxe_doc: Is an `EventHandler` representing the code to be called when the `fullscreenerror` event is raised.

onpointerlockchange.haxe_doc: Represents the event handling code for the `pointerlockchange` event.

onpointerlockerror.haxe_doc: Represents the event handling code for the `pointerlockerror` event.

visibilityState.haxe_doc: Returns a `string` denoting the visibility state of the document. Possible values are `visible`, `hidden`, `prerender`, and `unloaded`.

onvisibilitychange.haxe_doc: Is an `EventHandler` representing the code to be called when the `visibilitychange` event is raised.

selectedStyleSheetSet.haxe_doc: Returns which style sheet set is currently in use.

iterations.haxe_doc: The number of times the animation should repeat. Defaults to `1`, and can also take a value of `Infinity` to make it repeat for as long as the element exists.

iterationStart.haxe_doc: Describes at what point in the iteration the animation should start. 0.5 would indicate starting halfway through the first iteration for example, and with this value set, an animation with 2 iterations would end halfway through a third iteration. Defaults to 0.0.

fill.haxe_doc: Dictates whether the animation's effects should be reflected by the element(s) prior to playing (`"backwards"`), retained after the animation has completed playing (`"forwards"`), or `both`. Defaults to `"none"`.

endDelay.haxe_doc: The number of milliseconds to delay after the end of an animation. This is primarily of use when sequencing animations based on the end time of another animation. Defaults to 0.

easing.haxe_doc: The rate of the animation's change over time. Accepts the pre-defined values `"linear"`, `"ease"`, `"ease-in"`, `"ease-out"`, and `"ease-in-out"`, or a custom `"cubic-bezier"` value like `"cubic-bezier(0.42, 0, 0.58, 1)"`. Defaults to `"linear"`.

duration.haxe_doc: The number of milliseconds each iteration of the animation takes to complete. Defaults to 0. Although this is technically optional, keep in mind that your animation will not run if this value is 0.

direction.haxe_doc: Whether the animation runs forwards (`normal`), backwards (`reverse`), switches direction after each iteration (`alternate`), or runs backwards and switches direction after each iteration (`alternate-reverse`). Defaults to `"normal"`.

delay.haxe_doc: The number of milliseconds to delay the start of the animation. Defaults to 0.

bubbles.haxe_doc: A Boolean indicating whether the event bubbles up through the DOM or not.

returnValue.haxe_doc: A historical property introduced by Internet Explorer and eventually adopted into the DOM specification in order to ensure existing sites continue to work. Ideally, you should try to use `Event.preventDefault()` and `Event.defaultPrevented` instead, but you can use `returnValue` if you choose to do so.

composed.haxe_doc: A Boolean value indicating whether or not the event can bubble across the boundary between the shadow DOM and the regular DOM.

isTrusted.haxe_doc: Indicates whether or not the event was initiated by the browser (after a user click for instance) or by a script (using an event creation method, like event.initEvent).

timeStamp.haxe_doc: The time at which the event was created (in milliseconds). By specification, this value is time since epoch, but in reality browsers' definitions vary; in addition, work is underway to change this to be a `DOMHighResTimeStamp` instead.

cancelBubble.haxe_doc: A historical alias to `Event.stopPropagation()`. Setting its value to `true` before returning from an event handler prevents propagation of the event.

originalTarget.haxe_doc: The original target of the event, before any retargetings (Mozilla-specific).

explicitOriginalTarget.haxe_doc: The explicit original target of the event (Mozilla-specific).

composedPath.haxe_doc: Returns the event’s path (objects on which listeners will be invoked). This does not include nodes in shadow trees if the shadow root was created with its `ShadowRoot.mode` closed.

stopPropagation.haxe_doc: Stops the propagation of events further along in the DOM.

stopImmediatePropagation.haxe_doc: For this particular event, no other listener will be called. Neither those attached on the same element, nor those attached on elements which will be traversed later (in capture phase, for instance)

preventDefault.haxe_doc: Cancels the event (if it is cancelable).

initEvent.haxe_doc: Initializes the value of an Event created. If the event has already being dispatched, this method does nothing.

variant.haxe_doc: Is a `CSSOMString` that contains the variant of the font. It is equivalent to the `@font-face/font-variant` descriptor.

status.haxe_doc: Indicates the font-face's loading status. It will be one of `'loading'` or `'loaded'`.

state.haxe_doc: Returns an `any` value representing the state at the top of the history stack. This is a way to look at the state without having to wait for a `popstate` event.

go.haxe_doc: Loads a page from the session history, identified by its relative location to the current page, for example -1 for the previous page or 1 for the next page. If you specify an out-of-bounds value (for instance, specifying -1 when there are no previously-visited pages in the session history), this method silently has no effect. Calling `go()` without parameters or a value of 0 reloads the current page. Internet Explorer lets you also specify a string to go to a specific page in the history list. @throws DOMError

pushState.haxe_doc: Pushes the given data onto the session history stack with the specified title and, if provided, URL. The data is treated as opaque by the DOM; you may specify any JavaScript object that can be serialized. Note that Firefox currently ignores the title parameter; for more information, see manipulating the browser history. @throws DOMError

replaceState.haxe_doc: Updates the most recent entry on the history stack to have the specified data, title, and, if provided, URL. The data is treated as opaque by the DOM; you may specify any JavaScript object that can be serialized. Note that Firefox currently ignores the title parameter; for more information, see manipulating the browser history. @throws DOMError

height.haxe_doc: Is a `DOMString` that reflects the `height` HTML attribute, indicating the height of the frame.

referrerPolicy.haxe_doc: Is a `DOMString` that reflects the `referrerPolicy` HTML attribute indicating which referrer to use when fetching the linked resource.

contentDocument.haxe_doc: Returns a `Document`, the active document in the inline frame's nested browsing context.

contentWindow.haxe_doc: Returns a `WindowProxy`, the window proxy for the nested browsing context.

align.haxe_doc: Is a `DOMString` that specifies the alignment of the frame with respect to the surrounding context.

scrolling.haxe_doc: Is a `DOMString` that indicates whether the browser should provide scrollbars for the frame.

frameBorder.haxe_doc: Is a `DOMString` that indicates whether to create borders between frames.

longDesc.haxe_doc: Is a `DOMString` that contains the URI of a long description of the frame.

marginHeight.haxe_doc: Is a `DOMString` being the height of the frame margin.

marginWidth.haxe_doc: Is a `DOMString` being the width of the frame margin.

width.haxe_doc: Is an `unsigned` `long` representing the width, in CSS pixels, of the `ImageData`.

height.haxe_doc: Is an `unsigned` `long` representing the height, in CSS pixels, of the `ImageData`.

close.haxe_doc: Disposes of all graphical resources associated with an `ImageBitmap`.

width.haxe_doc: Is an `unsigned` `long` representing the actual width, in pixels, of the `ImageData`.

height.haxe_doc: Is an `unsigned` `long` representing the actual height, in pixels, of the `ImageData`.

data.haxe_doc: Is a `Uint8ClampedArray` representing a one-dimensional array containing the data in the RGBA order, with integer values between `0` and `255` (included).

alt.haxe_doc: Is a `DOMString` that reflects the `alt` HTML attribute, thus indicating fallback context for the image.

src.haxe_doc: Is a `DOMString` that reflects the `src` HTML attribute, containing the full URL of the image including base URI.

srcset.haxe_doc: Is a `DOMString` reflecting the `srcset` HTML attribute, containing a list of candidate images, separated by a comma (`',', U+002C COMMA`). A candidate image is a URL followed by a `'w'` with the width of the images, or an `'x'` followed by the pixel density.

crossOrigin.haxe_doc: Is a `DOMString` representing the CORS setting for this image element. See CORS settings attributes for further details.

useMap.haxe_doc: Is a `DOMString` that reflects the `usemap` HTML attribute, containing a partial URL of a map element.

referrerPolicy.haxe_doc: Is a `DOMString` that reflects the `referrerpolicy` HTML attribute indicating which referrer to use in order to fetch the image.

isMap.haxe_doc: Is a `Boolean` that reflects the `ismap` HTML attribute, indicating that the image is part of a server-side image map.

width.haxe_doc: Is a `unsigned long` that reflects the `width` HTML attribute, indicating the rendered width of the image in CSS pixels.

height.haxe_doc: Is a `unsigned long` that reflects the `height` HTML attribute, indicating the rendered height of the image in CSS pixels.

decoding.haxe_doc: Returns a `DOMString` representing a hint given to the browser on how it should decode the image.

naturalWidth.haxe_doc: Returns a `unsigned long` representing the intrinsic width of the image in CSS pixels, if it is available; otherwise, it will show `0`.

naturalHeight.haxe_doc: Returns a `unsigned long` representing the intrinsic height of the image in CSS pixels, if it is available; else, it shows `0`.

complete.haxe_doc: Returns a `Boolean` that is `true` if the browser has finished fetching the image, whether successful or not. It also shows true, if the image has no `HTMLImageElement.src` value.

name.haxe_doc: Is a `DOMString` representing the name of the element.

align.haxe_doc: Is a `DOMString` indicating the alignment of the image with respect to the surrounding context. The possible values are `"left"`, `"right"`, `"justify"`, and `"center"`.

hspace.haxe_doc: Is a `long` representing the space on either side of the image.

vspace.haxe_doc: Is a `long` representing the space above and below the image.

longDesc.haxe_doc: Is a `DOMString` representing the URI of a long description of the image.

border.haxe_doc: Is a `DOMString` that is responsible for the width of the border surrounding the image. This is now deprecated and the CSS `border` property should be used instead.

sizes.haxe_doc: Is a `DOMString` reflecting the `sizes` HTML attribute.

currentSrc.haxe_doc: Returns a `DOMString` representing the URL to the currently displayed image (which may change, for example in response to media queries).

lowsrc.haxe_doc: Is a `DOMString` that refers to a low-quality (but faster to load) copy of the image.

x.haxe_doc: Returns a `long` representing the horizontal offset from the nearest layer. This property mimics an old Netscape 4 behavior.

y.haxe_doc: Returns a `long` representing the vertical offset from the nearest layer. This property is also similar to behavior of an old Netscape 4.

align.haxe_doc: `string:` represents the alignment of the element. Use CSS instead.

iterations.haxe_doc: The number of times the animation should repeat. Defaults to `1`, and can also take a value of `Infinity` to make it repeat for as long as the element exists.

iterationStart.haxe_doc: Describes at what point in the iteration the animation should start. 0.5 would indicate starting halfway through the first iteration for example, and with this value set, an animation with 2 iterations would end halfway through a third iteration. Defaults to 0.0.

fill.haxe_doc: Dictates whether the animation's effects should be reflected by the element(s) prior to playing (`"backwards"`), retained after the animation has completed playing (`"forwards"`), or `both`. Defaults to `"none"`.

endDelay.haxe_doc: The number of milliseconds to delay after the end of an animation. This is primarily of use when sequencing animations based on the end time of another animation. Defaults to 0.

easing.haxe_doc: The rate of the animation's change over time. Accepts the pre-defined values `"linear"`, `"ease"`, `"ease-in"`, `"ease-out"`, and `"ease-in-out"`, or a custom `"cubic-bezier"` value like `"cubic-bezier(0.42, 0, 0.58, 1)"`. Defaults to `"linear"`.

duration.haxe_doc: The number of milliseconds each iteration of the animation takes to complete. Defaults to 0. Although this is technically optional, keep in mind that your animation will not run if this value is 0.

direction.haxe_doc: Whether the animation runs forwards (`normal`), backwards (`reverse`), switches direction after each iteration (`alternate`), or runs backwards and switches direction after each iteration (`alternate-reverse`). Defaults to `"normal"`.

delay.haxe_doc: The number of milliseconds to delay the start of the animation. Defaults to 0.
